{"type":"message","id":"840b6cb7","parentId":"9fb39535","timestamp":"2026-04-21T14:20:45.592Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Docker Hub pull failed due to the network timing out. The registry mirrors might not have the older version. Let me try again without specifying a tag (latest), but this time I'll just try using the latest version since the mirror seems to have connectivity issues.\n\nActually, the original searxng:latest is already pulled locally (we saw it 13 minutes ago). Let me just start it without the limiter/public_instance settings, and configure those properly without the Valkey requirement.\n\nActually, let me think about the simplest path to success:\n1. Start searxng with the current config (latest version)\n2. Disable limiter completely (via settings.yml only, no env var override)  \n\n\n3. Keep public_instance false\n4. Fix the 403 by configuring the outgoing settings\n\nOr maybe I should step back and check if the limiter is even the real issue here. The 403 Forbidden might be coming from an `http://` engine setting somewhere in the outbound connections, or maybe I'm missing a specific configuration detail in the searxng docs about what actually causes that error.\n\nLooking at what I know: the `limiter.toml` exists, Redis is running, yet the worker is still crashing with that atexit error. This feels like a bug in the newer SearXNG version, so downgrading to 2024.6.0 makes sense, but the mirror pull timed out. Let me try pulling the image directly without the mirror first to see if that's the bottleneck."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_nqm442mrau0z_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Retry pull latest from docker.io directly\ndocker pull docker.io/searxng/searxng:latest 2>&1 | tail -5","yieldMs":60000}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheR