{"type":"message","id":"fe04f3ee","parentId":"47303f8e","timestamp":"2026-04-21T14:23:13.231Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The settings still have `public_instance: true` and `limiter: true` from the previous container run. The volume `searxng-config` persisted these settings. The new container is using the same volume and still has those settings.\n\nBut the warning says \"Be aware you have activated features intended only for public instances. This force the usage of the limiter and link_token\" - which means limiter is still active and causing 429 errors.\n\nI need to:\n1. Set `public_instance: false` and `limiter: false` in the settings\n2. Also remove the limiter.toml since it's not needed\n\n\n3. Restart the container for changes to take effect\n\nWait, I realize the volume mount is at `/etc/searxng`, so when I ran `docker exec searxng sed -i ...` earlier, it should have modified the file directly, but the new container is still reading `public_instance: true`. Let me verify what's actually in the volume now.\n\nActually, I see the issue - I ran the sed command on a previous container instance. Even though the volume persists, that container was removed and replaced with a fresh one that started before I ran the sed command. So the new container never picked up those changes. I need to run the sed command again on the current container and then restart it."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_5fv2k8e2jqcu_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker exec searxng sed -i 's/  public_instance: true/  public_instance: false/' /etc/searxng/settings.yml\ndocker exec searxng sed -i 's/^  limiter: true/  limiter: false/' /etc/searxng/settings.yml\ndocker exec searxng rm -f /etc/searxng/limiter.toml\ndocker restart searxng && sleep 6\ndocker logs searxng --tail 5"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{