{"type":"message","id":"361cab8b","parentId":"3b779b0d","timestamp":"2026-04-21T14:25:40.535Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The machine running the docker containers has IP 192.168.31.146 - which is the same IP the user is accessing! So the SearXNG container is running on the same machine the user is testing from. The docker port mapping shows 0.0.0.0:8888->8888/tcp which should work.\n\nBut the curl from within the docker network is showing \"connection refused\" on 192.168.31.146:8888. This might be because the docker daemon's network is different from the host's wlp2s0 interface.\n\nActually, wait - the `docker port searxng` shows `8888/tcp -> 0.0.0.0:8888` which means the container's port 8888 is mapped to the host's 0.0.0.0:8888. \n\nThe issue is that `192.168.31.146:8888` is the host's wlp2s0 interface, but when a process in the container tries to connect to that address, it's trying to reach the host's wlp2s0 interface from within the docker network - which might not be directly accessible. The `docker exec` commands show the container can't reach `192.168.31.146:8888` even though the host machine itself has that IP, suggesting the docker network and host network are on different interfaces.\n\nSince both the searxng container and the host share the same IP 192.168.31.146 on wlp2s0, they should theoretically be on the same network, but the container's view of that interface might be different or limited. I should try using `host.docker.internal` or the gateway IP instead, or test with `127.0.0.1` with the proper port mapping to see if that resolves the connectivity issue."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qr97xlkbjdjp_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker exec searxng cat /etc/hosts | tail -5; docker exec searxng route -n 2>/dev/null | head -10"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{