{"type":"message","id":"f4c19415","parentId":"eaeecbf2","timestamp":"2026-04-21T14:26:52.339Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The container can't reach `localhost:8888` (connection refused). Let me check the actual port mapping and network.\n\nWait, the searxng container internal process listens on port 8080, but maps to host port 8888. From within the searxng container, `localhost:8080` should work... but actually from within the container, `localhost` refers to the container's own localhost, not the host's localhost.\n\nSo from inside the searxng container:\n- Port 8080 is the internal process port\n- Port 8888 on the container is mapped to host's 8888, but localhost:8888 from inside the container would try to connect to the container's port 8888, which is NOT the searxng process (the process is on 8080).\n\nSo `http://127.0.0.1:8080/search?q=openclaw&format=json&limit=2` is the correct URL from inside the container.\n\nBut it's still returning 403. And the `SEARXNG_LIMITER=false` env var IS being read (we confirmed it). So limiter is off, public_instance is false.\n\nLet me look at the actual SearXNG source code to understand why JSON format returns 403.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the settings more carefully. Let me look at lines around line 100 for the server section."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_mdsvkq10ougq_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker exec searxng sed -n '90,115p' /etc/searxng/settings.yml"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776781602188,"responseId":"0636bc22d666b4042535a3543461ff25"}}
{"type":"message","id":"bfe380aa","parentId":"f4c19415","timestamp":"2026-04-21T14:26:52.477Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_mdsvkq10ougq_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"port: 8888\n  bind_address: \"127.0.0.1\"\n  # public URL of the instance, to ensure correct inbound links. Is overwritten\n  # by ${SEARXNG_BASE_URL}.\n  base_url: false  # \"http://example.com/location\"\n  # rate limit the number of request on the instance, block some bots.\n  # Is overwritten by ${SEARXNG_LIMITER}\n  limiter: false\n  # enable features designed only for public instances.\n  # Is overwritten by ${SEARXNG_PUBLIC_INSTANCE}\n  public_instance: false\n\n  # If your instance owns a /etc/searxng/settings.yml file, then set the following\n  # values there.\n\n  secret_key: \"Smgy9ySarHjbpOEABdnYvusnZQtucy26\"  # Is overwritten by ${SEARXNG_SECRET}\n  # Proxy image results through SearXNG. Is overwritten by ${SEARXNG_IMAGE_PROXY}\n  image_proxy: false\n  # 1.0 and 1.1 are supported\n  http_protocol_version: \"1.0\"\n  # POST queries are \"more secure!\" but are also the source of hard-to-locate\n  # annoyances, which is why GET may be better for end users and their browsers.\n  # see https://github.com/searxng/searxng/pull/3619\n  # Is overwritten by ${SEARXNG_METHOD}\n  method: \"POST\"\n  default_http_headers:"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":84,"aggregated":"port: 8888\n  bind_address: \"127.0.0.1\"\n  # public URL of the instance, to ensure correct inbound links. Is overwritten\n  # by ${SEARXNG_BASE_URL}.\n  base_url: false  # \"http://example.com/location\"\n  # rate limit the number of request on the instance, block some bots.\n  # Is overwritten by ${SEARXNG_LIMITER}\n  limiter: false\n  # enable features designed only for public instances.\n  # Is overwritten by ${SEARXNG_PUBLIC_INSTANCE}\n  public_instance: false\n\n  # If your instance owns a /etc/searxng/settings.yml file, then set the following\n  # values there.\n\n  secret_key: \"Smgy9ySarHjbpOEABdnYvusnZQtucy26\"  # Is overwritten by ${SEARXNG_SECRET}\n  # Proxy image results through SearXNG. Is overwritten by ${SEARXNG_IMAGE_PROXY}\n  image_proxy: false\n  # 1.0 and 1.1 are supported\n  http_protocol_version: \"1.0\"\n  # POST queries are \"more secure!\" but are also the source of hard-to-locate\n  # annoyances, which is why GET may be better for end users and their browsers.\n  # see https://github.com/searxng/searxng/pull/3619\n  # Is overwritten by ${SEARXNG_METHOD}\n  method: \"POST\"\n  default_http_headers:","cwd":"/home/halei/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776781612463}}
{"type":"message","id":"29b6a027","parentId":"bfe380aa","timestamp":"2026-04-21T14:27:15.160Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! I see:\n- `bind_address: \"127.0.0.1\"` - SearXNG is bound to 127.0.0.1 inside the container, meaning it only listens on the loopback interface inside the container. The port mapping `8888:8888` maps host port 8888 to container port 8888, but the container process is listening on 127.0.0.1:8080 inside the container.\n\nWait, that doesn't make sense. The port mapping should still work because even if the process listens on 127.0.0.1 inside the container, Docker's port mapping (`-p 8888:8888`) creates a DNAT rule that forwards traffic from the host's 0.0.0.0:8888 to the container's 172.17.0.x:8888, which then gets forwarded to 127.0.0.1:8080... or does it?\n \nActually, I'm second-guessing myself on how Docker's port mapping works. The `-p 8888:8888` flag should forward traffic from the host's 0.0.0.0:8888 to the container's internal IP on port 8888, not to 127.0.0.1 inside the container. But if the container process is listening on 127.0.0.1:8080 instead of 0.0.0.0:8888, the port mapping wouldn't actually reach it.\n\nWait, I need to reconsider this. Even though `EXPOSE 8888` is in the Dockerfile and `-p 8888:8888` maps it, if the application inside the container is bound to `127.0.0.1:8080` rather than `0.0.0.0:8888`, Docker's port-mapping system would need to handle the redirection between the exposed port and the internal binding. Let me think through whether that's actually how it works or if there's a disconnect here. I'm realizing I might be conflating two different SearXNG instances here. Let me trace back through the commands to figure out which container is actually running and whether the original searxng setup with the volume mount is still active or if there's been a port conflict with valkey running on 6379.\n\nThe real issue is that when I restart the searxng container with the same name, Docker preserves the volume mount to searxng-config, so the settings changes I made earlier should still be there. But now that I think about it, the first searxng container was created without a named volume, just an ephemeral filesystem—so those initial settings might have been lost when that container was removed.\n\nWait, but the grep output is showing `limiter: false`, which matches what I set in the second run. And the `bind_address: \"127.0.0.1\"` is suspicious—that might be what's blocking external access. The problem could be that SearXNG is binding to localhost inside the container, which would prevent it from accepting connections from outside.\n\nBut then again, curl to localhost:8888 from the host is hanging entirely, not just getting a 403 or connection refused. That's different from what I'd expect if the bind address was the issue. Let me look at what the actual container state is right now to understand what's happening."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_1ile2dh96u1k_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker ps -a | grep searxng\ndocker exec searxng netstat -tlnp 2>/dev/null || docker exec searxng ss -tlnp 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776781612481,"responseId":"0636bc2d9caeb721743f928ecd100b71"}}
