{"type":"message","id":"5bc0a763","parentId":"56ba345d","timestamp":"2026-04-21T14:36:47.025Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Docker Hub seems to be completely blocked right now. I can't pull any new images. The searxng image is cached so it's still working.\n\nOK let me think about this completely differently. The issue is:\n1. searxng is running and listening on port 8888 inside the container\n2. Port mapping 8888->8888 exists \n3. But curl to 127.0.0.1:8888 gives \"Empty reply from server\"\n\nWait - actually, I just realized something. Looking at the earlier successful tests:\n- `docker exec searxng wget -O - \"http://127.0.0.1:8080/search?q=openclaw\"` returned HTML (200 OK)\n\n\n- But `curl -s \"http://127.0.0.1:8888/search?q=openclaw\"` gives empty reply\n\nThe difference is wget runs inside the container talking to the internal port 8080, while curl is running on the host going through the mapped port 8888. So something is wrong with how the port mapping is actually working.\n\nLet me reconsider what's happening here. When I run the container with port publishing, Docker should set up iptables rules to forward traffic from the host's 0.0.0.0:8888 to the container's internal 8080. The fact that searxng binds to :::8080 in the container and the mapping shows 0.0.0.0:8888->8888/tcp looks correct, but clearly the traffic isn't getting through properly.\n\nLet me test with a different service to isolate whether this is a Docker networking issue or something specific to searxng's configuration.\n\nActually, wait—I'm noticing something about those earlier wget tests. When wget ran inside the container against 127.0.0.1:8080, it worked and got HTML back. But curl from the host to 127.0.0.1:8888 is getting an empty reply. The discrepancy is odd—either the service isn't actually listening on the mapped port, or there's something about how the connection is being handled differently between the two methods.\n\nLet me step back and check if there's a network-level issue. I should try connecting directly to the container's internal IP rather than relying on the port mapping, or test with a completely different approach to see if Docker's networking itself is working as expected."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_t30piexxd4vm_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker inspect searxng --format '{{range .NetworkSettings.Networks}}{{.IPAddress}}{{end}}'\ndocker exec searxng ss -tlnp 2>/dev/null | grep 8080"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776782190211,"responseId":"0636be6e58a1bbda69369f20bc161e90"}}
