{"type":"message","id":"ab7f53de","parentId":"9cfacf76","timestamp":"2026-04-21T14:39:37.830Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is taking too long. Let me try a different approach - just use `public_instance=false` and figure out why JSON is being blocked when the config clearly says it's disabled.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The issue might be that the `searxng-config` volume has the old `public_instance=true` configuration cached. When I run without a volume, it should use defaults. But then I apply `sed` to change settings which takes effect... but the restart reloads from volume.\n\nActually wait - when I run without `-v searxng-config:/etc/searxng`, the settings should be default. Then I `sed` to change them. \n\nAfter restart, settings persist in the volume. But if I run without volume, it starts fresh with defaults each time - yet `public_instance: false` still blocks JSON API access. That suggests the issue isn't the config itself but something in how the binary handles this version, or possibly Docker's port mapping on this particular machine rejecting connections.\n\nI'm suspecting the host's firewall or network setup is intercepting port 8888 and dropping packets. Even simpler tests with nginx fail the same way, so this might be broader than just SearXNG. I should try hosting on a different port like 8081 to see if that bypasses whatever's blocking 8888."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_3mfhkb95z6d6_1","name":"process","arguments":{"action":"kill","sessionId":"vivid-bloom"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776782367618,"responseId":"0636bf1fd23e3c46018f25920739623d"}}
